snippet.textDisplay:
I like the manual nature of the dip pen and noise it makes.
I will also mention that the water well it came with is no good because the glass on glass contact can break the pen and it is not big enough.
Also he needs to wait for the ink to dry a good long while before he adds more ink, different colors, or trys to erase.
Other useful tips include getting rubbing alcohol for cleaning the pen and getting water proof ink that he can color over.

Sorry for the long post! It was finally a subject I knew something about!

I've switch from using microns to fountain pens on my art.

snippet.textDisplay: So the reason why the ink spread during erasing is due to either the ink not fully drying (which you said it had) or the paper not being compatable with that particular ink. Some papers take fountain pen ink better than others. But since this looked like a not great inexpensive ink and glass pen set (none of the well known ink companies would put out a bottle with terrible text like "a hippopotamus is a hippopotamus") it could be a fault of the ink itself. With a decent ink from one of the better known brands, you should be able to erase pencil after the ink dries.
snippet.textOriginal: So the reason why the ink spread during erasing is due to either the ink not fully drying (which you said it had) or the paper not being compatable with that particular ink. The lines were not even and when you made short lines vs longer ones the difference in thickness truly showed more as, the start might be a bit of a droplet like start that ended in a nice sharp point. That offers a drawing such a beautiful ART stile vs what standard pens offer. I think if you were to do a cross hatch drawing for example and not a drawing like you did here, you would see a truly amazing and beautiful looking piece compared to what your normal drawing pens offer.

Like, if you did a drawing like this:
https://youtu.be/AHoqh27vQRw

snippet.textDisplay: Fountain pen people who are more into collecting inks than pens will often use these to test and swatch their ink collection. Using it with a different kind of ink that is quick drying and doesn't smear would solve your problem. You could look at recommendations for lefty fountain pen users to find those. And fraud-proof inks will even survive watercolor without getting everywhere. ETA: You can also use it for pigments derived from natural sources like tea, if you were so inclined, since you don't have to worry about damage to brush bristles or corrosion of a metal nib.
